<TABLE BORDER=0 cellpadding=4 border=0 cellspacing=1 WIDTH="95%"><TR bgcolor="#D5E6E1"><TD COLSPAN=2><CENTER><FONT SIZE="2" COLOR="#000080" FACE="Verdana, Arial">T O P I C  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; R E V I E W</font></CENTER></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#dedfdf"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Jacob</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">  The other night I joined a pickup group in KC, that was camping the Dog Capt. First pull after me joining was the Capt he dropped Cobalt guants. I didnt roll cause I just joined and they warrior only. Everyone rolled chanter won. They said this is an "everyone rolls group". That is rare for KC but I accepted it. An hour later a warrior joins us, and within 15min the Capt spawns and drops the guants again. We all rolled and a monk won. The warrior proceeded to throw a tantrum, he rolled to but lost, called us all names and left the group. He then started giving us all tells, me included. I told him "this is a FFA group". He then started to threaten and harass me. He said he was gonna put my name on all the boards claiming I am a loot whore. I got mad and told him "You can do what you want, but if I won the guants they be in my bag now". <BR>  During the argument I said nothing. I was torn between the sides. He was only warrior in group and should get guants. Group rule is everyone rolls. I have already noticed this warrior posting on diff sites about the conflict.<BR>  This warrior was and is acting very immature. The monk that won the guants posted that he would give him the guants just to clear up this prob. I give alot of respect to the monk for that. After all the threats and harassment I would never, EVER give him those guants. <BR>  If I won the roll I would have given him the guants right there. After the way the warrior is acting I am sooo glad I lost.<BR>  I checked the board again and found someone who said this warrior has won cobalt guants before and sold them. If that is true then he is using the NBG rule to be a loot whore himself.<BR>  Anyway, that is what happened. Any comment on a diff way I should have handled it would be appreciated.<P>Jake level 51 Vicar</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#f7f7f7"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Aladain</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">This is another example of reason why you MUST explain the loot rules EVERY TIME **ESPECIALLY** when a class comes to a camp that drops his goodies. (i.e. Warrior to capt group).<P>I'd be pissed too, but I wouldn't throw that kind of fit like he did.  I *ALWAYS* ask when camping hands, etc "If donals gaunts drop, are we rolling, or are they NBG?".  If they roll, I say they can find another cleric and move on.  I've never had a problem with this.<P>Aladain</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#dedfdf"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Myc</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">You really are in a no-win situation.  Yes, as the other poster said, always explain loot rules.  However no one will ever be satisfied.<P>I was in the same situation as you.  The Cobalt gauntlets dropped.  A warrior was in the group.  It was NBG, however the main person was a little shy.  So I insisted that the warrior take them since she could use.  The enchanter promptly disbanded, and we later found out because it was NBG.<P>So you will find greedy people everywhere.  I'm not sure what the solution is.  If it is NBG, people will get mad.  If everyone rolls, people will get mad.  I personally prefer NBG in KC, mainly because if something drops I could use, I would hate for a monk or someone to win the roll and loot it.  Normally if you stay long enough you can get SOMETHING in KC.  Whether it be some Kunark armor, a Sarnak Hide Mask, etc.<P>Just don't worry too much about it.  And keep track of the childish people, so that if something drops that only they can use, you can remind them of what they thought of NBG before.  Or vice-versa.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#f7f7f7"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Aquinas</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">One moral of the story: always explain loot rules to people who join the group.  As noted, this does not solve every problem, as some people are just immature.<P>Another moral of the story: avoid Karnor's Castle. I don't know if that zone attracts the worst people in EQ, or just brings out the worst in otherwise normal people.  Either way, I find it a demoralizing place.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#dedfdf"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Hinanar</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial"><BR>If the group had told the warrior that it was a 'FFA' group, then the warrior is at fault.<P>If they hadn't, I would understand why he was upset.<P>------------------<BR>Hinanar Goodhammer<BR>Vicar of Brell Seliris<BR>Cazic-Thule Server<BR>Guild of Albion "Death before Dishonour!"<P>'Clerics can tank...we're just no good at dealing damage'</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#f7f7f7"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Uulax</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">First mistake:  You were in Karnor's, bastion for the idiots of Norrath.  Don't go there.  Go someplace where the average player IQ is above 25, someplace like Sebilis.<P>If I were in your situation, I'd just say "I'm not the leader, I didn't make the rules, shut up and get over it."  If they won't shut up, put them on /ignore.<P>Good players will look for the fairest lotto situation, but they will also accept small things that happen and move on.  Obviously, the group didn't look for the fairest lotto situation, and the Warrior couldn't get over losing a 10k item he'd replace in 2 months anyway, so you're left with a bunch of bad players at the core of the problem.<P>Which brings us back to mistake number 1.   <IMG SRC="http://eqcleric.gameglow.com/ubb/biggrin.gif"></FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#dedfdf"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Nalance</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">I play on Jake's server and every time I've been in Karnor (for a couple of months now), the loot rule was need before greed.  This is the first group I've heard of that is FFA.  <P>I do not know which side is right in this case as I was not there.  As to the person seen selling gauntlets previously, that was only confirmed by a member in the chanter or monk's guild (I can't remember which) and may or may not be true. <P>I know I would be upset if a piece of Donal's dropped and it was a FFA looting.  I have been there for a few months and have yet to see any Donal's drop.  I do have a lot of Jarcrap (oh I mean Jarsath) armor, but most of that rots cause you can't even give it away easily.  <IMG SRC="http://eqcleric.gameglow.com/ubb/smile.gif"></FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#f7f7f7"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Aladain</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial"> <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR>Originally posted by Aquinas:<BR><B>Another moral of the story: avoid Karnor's Castle. I don't know if that zone attracts the worst people in EQ, or just brings out the worst in otherwise normal people.  Either way, I find it a demoralizing place.</B><HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P>Few of you have mentioned this.  I have found the nicest people of all in Karnors.  Everyone gets along great, everyone NBGs (and it WORKS), and the people are always nice.<P>Sebilis on the other hand is usually full of punks IMO.<P>Aladain<P></FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#dedfdf"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Aliach</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Well the one time that I've been to KC, my experience was good, nothing dropped but it was a need group.  I really don't seen the point in Greed.  But yeah I'll have to agree with the others, if he knew it was a Greed group, then there was no reason for him to be whining..<P>------------------<BR>Aliach Cleric of the <A HREF="http://www.pathofhonor.com" TARGET=_blank>Path</A></FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#f7f7f7"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Zygote</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial"><BR>any player that would throw a tantrum after the lotto has taken place is greedy to begin with. <P>The best way to avoid situations like this though is to tell someone new that its FFA or NBG system as soon as they join.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#dedfdf"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Wisecleric</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Yup, it was the warriors fault for assuming the group was using NBG looting system. Luckily on my server in zones where pick-up groups are the norm, like Karnor and Seb, the default is /random (and it works great). He would have known going in that the group is probably going to be /randoming and therefore wouldnt have been that upset when thats the way it turned out to be. <P>Everyone in that group is taking the same risk. Everyone should have the same opportunity to improve their character through item acquisition. Whether they can use the item instantly (i.e. warrior and cobalt gauntlets) or if they can use the item to aquire a usable reward later (cleric trading them for a sarnak battle shield for example, which is hard to obatin in pickup-type groups). <P>Fight the greed! /random it all! <P><BR></FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#f7f7f7"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Aladain</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial"> <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR>Originally posted by Wisecleric:<BR><B>. Luckily on my server in zones where pick-up groups are the norm, like Karnor and Seb, the default is /random (and it works great). </B><HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P>And exactly who told the level 45 going into karnors for the first time this was the norm?<P>/random in my past on TP and Erollisi Marr servers have caused nothing but problems.  You end up with a cleric winning a pally item with a pally in the group winning a cleric item, but the cleric item might be worth 12k and the pally item might be worth only 4k, so they wont swap.<P>I dunno bout yall (and following Raynes advice, I'm not going to advocate this topic go to a NBG discussion) but I've NEVER had a problem with NBG.  The only time its a problem is if someone with NBG sells the item and expects it NBG next time.  I personally dont see a problem with that - VERY FEW people sell items received over NBG, and VERY MANY people get upset (reasonably, not a temper tantrum like that warrior) that their roll wasnt the winning one.  You hurt a lot more folks IMO.<P>Nuff of that  <IMG SRC="http://eqcleric.gameglow.com/ubb/smile.gif"><P>Aladain</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#dedfdf"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Wisecleric</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">"VERY FEW people sell items received over NBG,"<P>Thats really not very likely. Almost EVERY item someone gets is eventually sold, traded, or given away at some point. Usually its sold/trade to acquire better items. So in the end, the item is, pretty much, always used to acquire better items. In NBG, only certain members of a group are allowed to benifit from the item. In a /random group, everyone gets that opportunity. Which is more fair? Seem pretty obvious to me. <P>"and VERY MANY people get upset." <P>Its been my experience that the only people that get upset are the ones that are primarily thinking only of themselves. They REFUSE to see that that item can also benifit someone else. Why can't people be happy that another member of their group (who is risking the SAME as you) is granted the ability to improve their character? Its all me! me! me!. Bleh!  <P>If someone wins a piece of Donal's in my /random group, im happy for them. I hope they can use it to acquire a decent item they can use. I hope that it brings them some extra enjoyment from this game. Even if they sell it for plat and blow it all on tradeskills, im happy for them. Why is this type of attitude considered so "greedy"? Where does greed play ANY part in such mentality? Tell me, i would like to know. <P><BR></FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#f7f7f7"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Aladain</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Wisecleric,<P>I've gotten several things on NBG and still have.  You bet I'll sell or trade in the future, but they will get used quite a bit before that point - Quite a difference from a warrior winning a cleric item, and 5 seconds later, /auctioning the zone.<P>NBG has nothing to do with greed, it ensures that the item WILL get at least some use by someone who can use it and would use it before it gets traded, and passed on to someone else.   If you NBG *everything* on this premis, its in balance, because there are X cleric items that X clerics will win, and those X items will get used by the person that won it before they are passed on.  Under /random rules, its VERY likely for a_warrior01 to win a cleric item (or whatever other class item), and group breaks up, and next day a_warrior01 (same person) wins THE SAME item again.  Different group - but same cleric, and same warrior.  THATS greed.  Warrior 2, Cleric 0.  Meanwhile, a_cleric01 has to spend hours upon hours for what?  To hope that a group doesnt change, or that he gets lucky on a roll, or he ends up in a NBG group that he would get the item.  Maybe its only because I play on Thlouxe Paells, and for those that also play on this server - You know that NBG is everywhere, and its done RIGHT.  No one complains, and if someone even suggests a random on a item that someone else in the group that use, they are seen as being greedy.<P>As for the topic of being upset, and with what I said above - lets say you were camping hands in karnors for 5 levels, and a total of 5 donals gauntlets dropped, and THE SAME PERSON won that item each time, and subsequently sold it, I'd like to know how you'd feel, and if on the 5th time the warrior won that item, if the cleric asked him "Can I please have those, you've already won 4" would you consider that greed?<P>Sure, I'm happy when someone wins something, but at the same time, in karnors/seb/whatever, when cobalt drops, it goes to the warrior.  When donals drops, it goes to the cleric.  If cobalt drops, and warrior wants, I refuse to random it, or will openly say that I will give to the warrior if I win because he deserves it anyway.  He fought for it.  This crap about a mage getting it because he got lucky with dice is absolutely absurd.  When the mage item drops, he gets it.  Thats how it should work IMO.<P>Tell me, when you go to a newbie zone (I dont know if you've ever done this), and have a item, like a Blackened iron medallion, or other such lower-level item, and you /ooc "Find me and poke me for a free BIM", why are you doing this?  I do it all the time to help my fellow casters out on equipment.  I also say that only casters can participate because the LAST thing I want is a rogue for instance winning that to 5 seconds later /auction it off.  If that were the case, thats no different than me giving 100pp to someone in west freeport begging for money.<P>I'm not going to reply on this anymore, only cuz I dont wanna piss off Rayne, he seems to not like these NBG discussions, but I felt that playing on thlouxe paells, and the near-perfection of NBG looting, it needed to be said.  In fact, in all my 55 levels (I got 55 back today!!), I have never been in a group that wasn't NBG.<P>Aladain<BR>55th Season Templar of Tunare</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#dedfdf"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Veraphie</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Personally, I like NBG not because I think it's fair but because most people on Vazaelle won't whine if loot were distributed NBG.<P>Do I think it's fair? Nope, not really. You can't always get a group to camp you cleric items. Yes they tried to fix that with random drops in some dungeons, but there are just SO MANY more melee things, pure caster things that drop. As long as it's tradable, it's prefectly true that everyone should get a chance to random it. The only problem I have with randoming things is that I don't think spells should be randomed. Personally though, on Vazaelle, there's just too many people who have NBG embedded into them for me to want to try to convince them otherwise. <P>I'm fine with either policy, but I think wisecleric is right. And if you play enough, you'll eventually get nice gear. So who really cares? I don't think either side should be bashing the other.<P>Veraphie<BR>57 Templar, Vazaelle <A HREF="http://www.in-virtue.com" TARGET=_blank>www.in-virtue.com</A> </FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#f7f7f7"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Aladain</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Veraphie,<P>To each their own  <IMG SRC="http://eqcleric.gameglow.com/ubb/smile.gif">.  And I'm not bashing and I dont think Wisecleric is either - I'm just expressing frustration how its somehow reguarded fair that when a group breaks up, it "resets" the random rules, thus allowing the same people to win the same item multiple times, at times, in front of the same people they won that item in the first place.  Warrior01 wins Item01 that Cleric01 can use.  Group breaks up, 5 hours later, group reforms again with same Warrior01 and Cleric01, but rest in group are different.  Same item drops.  Warrior01 randoms because he sold the first item and can loot it again. He wins roll and gets item.  Fair?  No.<P>Random would totally work - provided the group never broke up until 6 people got the same items.<P>I agree with you about the spells, but how's that different from items?  They are both needed, and in fact, I swing more to randoming for spells than I do for items, though I still think both should be given to the class t